metadata.name: Composition #4 #9
metadata.description:
When I'm working on a problem, I never think about beauty. But when I've finished, if the solution is not beautiful... I know it's wrong.
[Buckminster Fuller]

I tried to hybridize, in a schematic way only, the architectural language of neoplasticism with some characteristics of Islamic architecture. The result seems to me to convey a certain elegance...
As with the other "Composition #" series, you can explore the model interactively in 3D space.

metadata.name: Julia's Magical Bulbs - 3rd 4th 5th Powers #91
metadata.description:
Julia's Magical Bulbs are 3D dimensional fractals, based on the Julia Sets of the Mandelbulb fractal.  In this edition we explore the 3rd, 4th and 5th powers.

The token is interactive, use your mouse-wheel to zoom-in and see all the little details. You will find a menu in the lower-right corner which allows you to play with the iterations and camera position. You can also render high-resolution images here.

A little bit of magic happens when you select low iteration values, perhaps your token will even default to this.

Technical:

Not all browsers support multi-threaded modules, the fallback mode is quite slow. Try Chrome if your browser is not supported.

Calculated in full 64-bit on the CPU (not the GPU) for more accurate and detailed images.

metadata.name: =DMT= #397
metadata.description:
The Spirit Molecule, an experience out of this world, available in this world.

What will you see when you take your =DMT=? I wish you a great trip.

Groups of color palettes, lines and bezier curves combine to create what sometimes looks like a sun, an eye, a flower, an explosion, a pair of wings or a combination of these.

I hope in the future Psychedelics will be accessible to people in controlled settings with professional care and support. 
The Ayahuasca ceremonies happening around the world are a good step in this direction.

Press 's' to save a 3000x3000 px PNG.

Created by UpOnlyFan in August 2022 with p5js.

metadata.name: Botanical Gardens #118
metadata.description:
Question shouldn't be, What is Art?
Just because the answer is quite simple, imagination and creation to inspire.
The question should be, What is Art without dimensions, colors, shades, inspiration, creativity, vibrancy, variations, etc... "NOTHING", we get above all from God's Creation(Art) and no man can ever be a bigger artist than God. 

I always had attraction towards the flowers, the colors, the creativity, the fragrance, all have enticed me to appreciate what we are blessed with.

Botanical Gardens is all about dimensions, colors, vibrancy, and variations.
In this project we go deep with sin & cos to generate patterns of flowers, in comes the Botany's premium color themes range which cover from fade to vibrant colors. Add with some onclick variations, you can always find the best possible locations for your flowers and save.

This project is token of my appreciation to God for blessing us all, with this amazing art surrounding us.

Click on NFT to see the flower dance.
Press "S" to save 1000x1000 png of your mint.
You are welcome to request a Hi-Res image for your holdings via twitter @TheRealBotany

metadata.name: VOYAGERS #82
metadata.description:
Generative animated painting made from looping gestures in a virtual void.

Voyagers is an exploration of automated gestures and screenspace layering effects. Each brush stroke sweeps through the canvas leaving a trail of color that either disappears or mixes with adjacent colors. The image slowly builds up to achieve an equilibrium between the rhythm of the gestures and the interaction of color values. These colors are quantized and dithered to produce chunky, textured, blocks of light that reify the materiality of the screen and the pixel. Two aspect ratios are possible, each with its own material relationship to screen-based work, 1:1 and 4:3 (vertical).

Press 's' to save looping animated GIF (live mode only).
Press 'p' to pause the animation.
Press 'c' to capture a single frame.
Made with P5.js and GLSL. By @galoandstuff.

metadata.name: Physarum Logo #535
metadata.description:
These past few months have been a great experience and with the beta ending, I wanted to create a piece to thank all collectors and pay tribute to this great platform. 

The piece is based on a physarum simulation with a couple of tweaks, such as continuous behavioural changes and an extra information layer that further manipulates the physarum.

There are ~262k particles simulated in parallel, so it is quite GPU heavy. 

Each piece features one of 12 different colour pallets, the text and a couple of cell-like bodies running around the screen.

Controls: 
S - Save image
H - Hide Text
Click/Touch - Spawn particles

Disclaimer: This is nothing official by the platform itself, merely a tribute by an artist and fan. 

With all that said: Thank you to everyone, and see you in 1.0 !

metadata.name: Dencity #879
metadata.description:
Dencity is a generative art project inspired by aerial views of cities with a high density of buildings. Its perspective effect, its perfectly imprecise lines, its subtle textures and its very advanced level of detail give it the appearance of a hand-drawn work.

Behind the visible art (the image) hides another form of art, an extremely complex algorithm capable of calculating and drawing in 2D each variation of the Dencity project. To draw a variation, the algorithm notably takes around 3,000,000 to 20,000,000 random decisions based on the hash of the mint and draws around 800,000 to 4,000,000 lines to create all the strokes and texture effects.

Made with ❤️, code and p5js.

metadata.name: Rococo #448
metadata.description:
Manual Dutch Auction (DA): 150 · 100 · 70 · 50 · 40 · 35 every 8 minutes. Auction will stop changing price when non-reserves are fully minted.

/////////////////////////////////////////////////////

Nature’s wild flourish and untamed growth wondrously represent the exacting function of beauty — a function that is at once useful and infinitely creative. Perhaps nowhere is this delicate symbiosis better observed than in the flower, wherein a pure balance of physical fundamentals exists beneath ornate patterns and elaborate aesthetics.

Amongst the layers of undulating, vividly colored petals, attention-grabbing stigma and stamen, and lusciously decorative features, nature’s organic abundance and disorder disguises its masterful propensity for precision. Each of the flower’s components evolve through unpredictable interactions with an unwieldy natural environment, creating spectacular adaptations that emerge from the tension between what attracts.

Rococo painters appreciated the organic fluidity found in flowers and vegetal forms, using their joyful abundance to depict a break from the rigid and stoic period the artists hoped to leave behind. They sought to reframe perfection away from predictability and toward compositions as surprising as the natural world around them.

Thus, ‘Rococo’ is a generative distortion of an old tradition: a digital painting created entirely with code that interprets and processes the natural world’s dichotomies. This painting algorithm builds upon natural structures while melding and moving their colors beyond form, growing randomly organic iterations that are as perfect as they are imperfect.

Created by Ori Ben-Shabat & Ronen Tanchum @Phenomenalabs
Creative contributions from Tender @tender_art

/////////////////////////////////////////////////////

Technical Details:

- Mobile/GPU Intensive
- Press “s” to save a .png of the artwork in live view
- Press “p” to render a high res output + press “s” to save a printable .png

metadata.name: Limina #198
metadata.description:
Limina is a study of the fine line between order and chaos.

Each piece of the collection is made up of just one or two lines. These lines are defined by thousands of points that are chosen, one by one, by a simple algorithm moving across the canvas. What arises from that simple concept is a surprising variety of intricate patterns, accidental symmetries and traces of order in chaotic structures. 

Limina is a meditation on the concept of emergence, a concept that lies at the heart of generative art. The algorithm that defines the core of the series is only capable of making one simple choice: left, right, up or down? As it moves across the canvas, it leaves a trace of points that are connected by a curve. The order in which these points are chosen and the tightness of the curve connecting them is what creates the visual diversity of Limina. As these values fluctuate, symmetries emerge and break down again, forms, patterns and ornaments are created and combined to form both complex structures and simple abstractions. 

Limina shows the potential of minimalist generative concepts to generate visually dense and unexpected results. 

Press 's' to save your image.
